assemblage.p:
If f(x) = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} c_k (x-a)^k converges for |x-a| \lt R for a positive real number R, then

  f'(x) = \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} k \cdot c_k (x-a)^{k-1}

and 

  \int f(x) \, dx = C + \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{c_k}{k+1} (x-a)^{k+1}

and both of these series converge if |x-a| \lt R.

subsection.p:
Recall that the sequence of partial sums oscillates around the sum S so that

  \left|S - S_n \right| \lt  \left| S_{n+1} - S_n \right| = a_{n+1}
.

statement.p:
Determine how well the 100th partial sum S_{100} of

  \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \frac{(-1)^{k+1}}{k}

approximates the sum of the series.
